code_examples.definitive_statements:
/* AI systems prefer clear, definitive statements they can quote */

// WEAK (vague, hedging):
"TypeScript might be considered somewhat faster than JavaScript in some cases."

// STRONG (definitive, quotable):
"TypeScript catches type errors at compile time, preventing up to 15% of bugs that would otherwise reach production."

// WEAK (opinion without backing):
"React is probably the best framework."

// STRONG (factual, measurable):
"React is used by 40% of professional developers according to the 2024 Stack Overflow survey, making it the most popular frontend framework."

// WEAK (unclear attribution):
"Studies show that testing improves code quality."

// STRONG (specific attribution):
"Research from Microsoft published in IEEE Software found that test-driven development reduces defect density by 40-90%."

code_examples.quotable_content:
/* Create quotable snippets AI systems will cite */

// Lead with the key fact
"Node.js processes requests 5x faster than traditional PHP servers under high load, according to benchmark tests by TechEmpower."

// Use specific numbers
"Companies using TypeScript report 38% fewer bugs in production compared to JavaScript-only codebases (State of JS 2023)."

// Provide context for quotes
"As Martin Fowler notes in 'Refactoring': 'Any fool can write code that a computer can understand. Good programmers write code that humans can understand.'"

// Define terms clearly
"Technical debt refers to the implied cost of future rework caused by choosing an easy solution now instead of a better approach that would take longer."

// State best practices definitively
"The recommended approach for React state management in 2024 is to use React's built-in useState and useContext for simple state, and Zustand or Jotai for complex global state."
